text: NearForm provides employees with a budget of €1,250 every two years that can be spent supporting them working remotely. This can be used on home office setup or can be put towards the cost of a co-working space. In principle, any physical equipment purchased is yours to keep. In the event that you leave NearForm less than 1 year after spending the budget, NearForm must be reimbursed for the spend. Note this policy supports remote working only; it does not cover education, training, wellness or fitness allowances. Note that NearForm applies this policy in principle, but due to jurisdictional tax laws (‘benefit in kind’ in particular), what can be covered by this allowance may vary country to country, but by and large use the following guidelines: Responsibility The NearForm People Team is responsible for the implementation and maintenance of this procedure. It is the responsibility of each Employee to provide a description of the spend and receipts It is the responsibility of the Line Manager to approve the expense Internal Process for Employee Remote Working Support Note there may be some jurisdictional variance, but in general: Employees discuss use of the budget with their line manager and complete this form (link:  https://forms.gle/aCefNvxwJKk85ZL1A ). Once the person completes the form it will automatically go to their line manager to approve If the line manager clicks the "Approve" button on the email notification then it automatically goes on to the People Team for final approval - The People Team then check to ensure the person has the required amount of budget left and "Approves" or "Declines" the application based on that If the line manager clicks the "Decline" button on the email notification then it bounces back to the applicant to tell them the application have been rejected by their manager (the manager can add comments to tell the applicant why it has been declined) If it is approved the employee carries out spend, a receipt for spend is submitted in Expensify (under Employee Remote Working Support), Line Manager is tagged for approval. Line Manager approves expense Allowed – no tax implications: Standing desk Chair Wifi equipment Monitor* Office furniture What you cannot claim for: Not allowed – tax implications: Heating bills Electricity bills Internet bills Cleaning bills Note NF provides Dell UltraSharp 25 Monitor – U2518D – 63.5cm(25″) Black as standard. This budget can be used for a second monitor if required.

Internal reading notes This document formalizes the creation of a formal NearForm Open Source Programme Office (NOSPO), and policy for what, when and how Open Source contributions can be made by NearForm staff that are in customer-facing delivery roles. We acknowledge that any policy cannot cover every single possibility; this document is intended to cover the majority of cases and if you have any queries about examples not covered under this policy, you should feel free to contact your line manager or NOSPO team. When this proposal is accepted, it should be integrated into the organization by: Assigning responsibility for this Policy to the NOSPO team Including it in the (bench) onboarding process Including it in the  thenearformway.com  portal Including it in the ISO documentation Overview NearForm is invested in and actively contributes to Open Source software. For NearForm staff that are in customer-facing, delivery roles, this document contains guidelines covering contributions to Open Source projects. This document covers Open Source contributions done during work hours and, in certain exceptional circumstances, in people’s own personal time. The diagram below illustrates the ‘what’ and ‘when’; NOSPO provides the ‘how’:  What NearForm allows time to be spent on contributions to Open Source projects that are important or relevant for the business. Projects for which NearForm will sponsor (i.e. allow working time on) contributions fall into three categories: NearForm-Sponsored Projects -- External Open Source projects that are not owned by, or are under the direct control of NearForm (external to any NearForm-owned GitHub organization) but to which NearForm has decided to allow staff to contribute to on NearForm-compensated time. Some NearFormers have commit access to these projects. Examples: Node.js, Fastify. Our participation and sponsorship in these communities is publicly marketed. NearForm-Owned Projects -- Open Source projects that are owned by, and are under the direct control of NearForm (internal to any NearForm-owned GitHub organization). Examples: Titus, Polaris, Mira, @nearfoform/sql. At times, open source efforts (for example, Lyra ( https://github.com/LyraSearch  ), are comprised of multiple repositories, warranting a separate organization.

You will find your annual leave allowance on NetSuite. The holiday year runs from 01 - January to 31 - December. Please note that not more than  5 days may be carried forward  to the next calendar year (any additional days over the 5 allowed will be lost) If you are taking leave, please ensure to set-up an ‘ Out of Office ’ on your email. You can also buy additional Annual Leave every year, for more information please  click here Procedure for Requesting Leave The request for leave must be submitted for approval by your manager to NetSuite. Submit in NetSuite by selecting ‘My new Time Off Request’ under your shortcuts and following these steps: Step 1 - Select the type of absence e.g. Annual Leave Step 2 - Select the start date of the request Step 3 - Change the end date of the request if required Step 4 - If you want to request a half day tick the start or end date is a half day checkbox Step 5 - If you are requesting a half day, enter the start time of your time off Step 6 - Click Save to Submit the Absence request for the approval of your Line Manager All leave must be pre-authorised by your Line Manager. Nearform considers that taking leave without authorisation a gross misconduct offence. Taking leave despite a declined request will be considered a gross misconduct offence. Gross misconduct offences may result in dismissal without notice. Notice Periods 2 weeks’ notice for less than 5 days 1 months’ notice for more than 5 days Special negotiation is required well in advance for longer holiday periods of over 2 weeks Whilst your Manager will endeavour to facilitate your request, it may be the case that due to busy periods/deadlines your Manager will not be in a position to approve; leave approval is at the discretion of the Manager. If you have any queries, please email peopleteam@nearform.com Delivery Team Please note Delivery management rely on foresight and planning where possible. Throughout the year, and particularly around busy periods such as Christmas and school holidays, please let your Technical Director know directly via email or slack as well as applying for annual leave in NetSuite, so that they are aware of the upcoming leave and can plan for it to have the least amount of disruption as possible to the project and your teammates. If you have any Delivery related queries regarding this policy please contact Clare Flinders, Delivery Ops Director ( clare.flinders@nearform.com ).

Where it all began … NearForm was founded in 2011 by Cian O’Maidin and Richard Rodger and hit the ground running in the early days of its life, initially based in  Arclabs Research & Innovation Centre  based on the outskirts of Waterford city. The company initially comprised a small number of outstanding developers based all over the world. NearForm began evangelizing the twin messages of Node.js and the scientific approach to building software, using every channel available: in-person networking, speaking engagements, posts on the NearForm blog, and Twitter. Early NearForm clients included the Sunday Business Post newspaper, Permanent TSB bank, Intel and Digitas. As time has passed, NearForm’s client list has expanded to include global names like Condé Nast, DPD and Intel. As the client list was expanding, so too was NearForm, adding more and more highly skilled people to its on-site team in Waterford. It wasn’t just software developers, an Office Manager and a Bookkeeper were among the earliest employees. Even with the addition of new rooms, the space in the incubation centre was bursting at the seams. A new premises was urgently needed. This posed a very important question: “ where do we want to be based? ” Cian and Richard had heard from a number of quarters that a high-potential technology company like NearForm needed to be in Silicon Valley. They made trips to the US, talked to a lot of people, and did a lot of soul-searching. This lead them to the realisation that two of NearForm’s core values were home and family. They wanted to raise their children in a place that gave them the quality of life that South-East Ireland offered. They wanted their partners to be able to live in a part of the world they loved. They wanted to be in a place where a sense of community and the natural environment were daily pleasures – and they wanted to be able to offer employees the same benefits. In the end, Cian, Richard and the NearForm team decided to turn a perceived weakness into a strength. NearForm HQ would stay in Ireland. Using a unique approach that combined remote working, family friendliness, and flexibility, with the stunning natural environment as a backdrop, they would turn the location into an advantage.
